{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c63695f3-f63b-4e04-935e-47db1f70a909","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:~/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** — open in Visual Studio, PerfView (Windows), or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (cross-platform). For Speedscope, convert first:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool install` isn't feasible (read-only filesystem), use the **`dotnet-monitor`** sidecar image instead — it exposes a REST API for trace collection.\n- For production, prefer **`--duration`** to avoid forgetting to stop.\n- `cpu-sampling` is low-overhead (~5%) and safe for production.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"19195c88-54ab-4d2e-8457-730117fbb70d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":424,"requestId":"1B82:94E9C:D14C5B:EE208F:6A0281D5"},"id":"5083dba0-6db6-4c15-ad0d-7adb968bd1bf","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:26:56.161Z","parentId":"93ff232e-409d-4a72-8416-34f0d1311ca8"}
